<section class="px-6 md:px-16 py-section" aria-labelledby="arnis-hero-heading">
  <p class="text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase opacity-40 mb-6">
    Lapunti Arnis de Abanico
  </p>

  <h1
    id="arnis-hero-heading"
    class="text-6xl md:text-8xl lg:text-[10rem] font-black tracking-[-0.04em] leading-[1.05] mb-8 max-w-5xl"
  >
    The Art<br />of the Fan
  </h1>

  <p class="text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed opacity-60 max-w-2xl mb-16">
    A Filipino martial art defined by fluid, fan-like striking patterns and
    precise footwork — where every movement flows from a single, unbroken
    principle.
  </p>

  <div
    class="border-t border-ink-50 pt-16 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-16"
  >
    <div>
      <h2
        class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black tracking-[-0.04em] leading-[1.05] mb-4"
      >
        Philosophy
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed opacity-60">
        Lapunti Arnis de Abanico is rooted in the principle that economy of
        motion is the highest form of power. The "abanico" — fan — is not merely
        a metaphor for the arc of the strike; it is the governing logic of the
        entire system. Each technique opens and closes like a fan: compact at
        the source, expansive at the point of contact, and immediately ready to
        redirect.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed opacity-60 mt-4">
        The art teaches that aggression without structure is noise. True mastery
        is the ability to neutralize force with the least possible effort — a
        discipline that demands patience, precision, and an unwillingness to
        settle for approximate.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2
        class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black tracking-[-0.04em] leading-[1.05] mb-4"
      >
        Lineage
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed opacity-60">
        Lapunti Arnis de Abanico traces its lineage through the fighting
        traditions of the Visayas region of the Philippines. The system was
        codified and preserved by masters who understood that the oral and
        physical transmission of technique is itself a form of cultural
        stewardship.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed opacity-60 mt-4">
        The name "Lapunti" honors the place of origin, while "de Abanico"
        describes the signature fanning motion that distinguishes this lineage
        from other Arnis and Eskrima systems. To practice Lapunti is to carry
        forward a living tradition — one that demands both technical rigor and
        deep respect for those who came before.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
